Create a cloud custodian policy to delete all not in use ECS task definitions for specific template. Add a flag to consider the definitions older than x day, if flag not passed, delete all definitions except active ones.
You can do this with an aws.ecs-task-definition policy that (a) filters to your template family, (b) optionally filters by age, and (c) excludes the active revision, then deletes the rest.

Below is a pattern you can parameterize with a “days” flag at run time (e.g., vars via CLI or Jinja):

text
vars:
  # Pass this from CLI/env; if empty -> delete all non-active
  # Example: custodian run -s out -v days=30 ecs-td-cleanup.yml
  days: ''

policies:
  - name: ecs-task-def-cleanup-for-template
    resource: aws.ecs-task-definition
    description: |
      Delete ECS task definitions for a specific template family
      that are not the currently active revision. If "days" is set (>0),
      only delete definitions older than that many days.
    filters:
      # 1) Only this template / family
      - type: value
        key: family
        op: eq
        value: my-template-family               # <-- your template name

      # 2) Exclude the currently active revision
      #    This keeps the latest ACTIVE TD for that family.
      - type: reduce
        sort-by:
          key: revision
          value_type: integer
        order: desc
        limit: 1
        op: difference

      # 3) Optional age filter: only when "days" is set
      - or:
          - and:
              - type: value
                key: registrationDate
                value_type: age
                op: gt
                value: 0
              - type: value
                key: registrationDate
                value_type: age
                op: gt
                value: "{{ days | int }}"
          # If days is empty or 0, this branch will not match anything,
          # so you effectively delete all non-active definitions.

    actions:
      - type: delete
        # force: true      # optional – deregister vs permanent delete[web:1]
How it behaves:

When days is not provided or set to 0:
The age filter does not effectively restrict the set, so all non-active task definitions for my-template-family are deleted (active one kept).

When days is set to X (e.g., 30):
Only task definitions for my-template-family that are older than X days and are not the latest active revision are deleted.

If you prefer not to use templating and want two explicit modes instead, I can rewrite this into two separate policies (one “delete all non-active” and one “delete older than X days”) wired to different Cloud Custodian runs; would that fit your workflow better?

