Here are two explicit policies, each wired to its own run, so you can call them separately from your pipelines or schedulers.

Policy 1 – Delete all non‑active task definitions for a template
This policy keeps the latest ACTIVE revision for the given family and deletes all older revisions (regardless of age).

text
policies:
  - name: ecs-td-delete-all-non-active
    resource: aws.ecs-task-definition
    description: |
      Delete all non-active ECS task definition revisions for a given family.
      Keeps only the latest ACTIVE revision.

    filters:
      # Limit to specific template / family
      - type: value
        key: family
        op: eq
        value: my-template-family      # <-- your template name

      # Remove the latest revision (assumed active) from the candidate set
      - type: reduce
        sort-by:
          key: revision
          value_type: integer
        order: desc
        limit: 1
        op: difference

    actions:
      - type: delete                  # deregister or delete based on your need
        # force: true                 # uncomment to permanently delete[web:1]
You would run this with something like:

bash
custodian run -s out ecs-td-delete-all-non-active.yml
Policy 2 – Delete non‑active task definitions older than X days
This policy deletes only non‑active revisions for the family that are older than a given age threshold, using registrationDate with value_type: age.

text
policies:
  - name: ecs-td-delete-old-non-active
    resource: aws.ecs-task-definition
    description: |
      Delete ECS task definition revisions for a given family that are not
      the latest ACTIVE revision and are older than X days.

    filters:
      # Limit to specific template / family
      - type: value
        key: family
        op: eq
        value: my-template-family      # <-- your template name

      # Remove the latest revision (assumed active) from the candidate set
      - type: reduce
        sort-by:
          key: revision
          value_type: integer
        order: desc
        limit: 1
        op: difference

      # Only those older than X days (e.g., 30)
      - type: value
        key: registrationDate
        value_type: age
        op: gt
        value: 30                      # <-- your X days

    actions:
      - type: delete
        # force: true                  # optional permanent delete[web:1]
You would run this from a separate workflow or schedule, for example:

bash
custodian run -s out ecs-td-delete-old-non-active.yml
If your “specific template” selection is more complex than just matching the family (for example, by tags or container image name within the task definition), do you want to match on family alone or on some other field as well?

